Industry News


                Technology            


GoDaddy wins lengthy patent infringement case that affects the tech industry




Jun 13, 2016, 2:06pm MST



Updated May 5, 2017, 3:15pm MST






Industries & Tags


                    Technology,                 



                    Government & Regulations                















Hayley Ringle


Reporter
Phoenix Business Journal













                    Share
                


























 Order Reprints


 Save Article




 Print
















 



 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Twitter




 Save Article





More 






 Email




 Facebook




 LinkedIn




 Order Reprints




 Twitter




 Save Article
























 













Hayley Ringle


Reporter
Phoenix Business Journal









 Enlarge





                                Nima Kelly is GoDaddy's… more 

                                Provided by GoDaddy                            







Related Content
            





                            GoDaddy buys California cloud communications company for $42 million                        





                            GoDaddy pledges to hire 500 military vets or spouses                        





                            GoDaddy reports revenue growth and lower net loss than a year ago                        



 






Home of the Day
        





 Sponsor Listing 



                    Beautiful New Construction in the Guard Gated Golf Community of Desert Highlands                




See All Homes of the Day





 











 Enlarge





                Brian LaCorte            








 



Scottsdale-based GoDaddy won a long-standing legal battle in Phoenix that could affect similar patent infringement claims against other technology companies.
RPost Communications Ltd., the Los Angeles-based creator of the RMail secure and certified electronic communications company that also is a patent holding company, claimed GoDaddy’s email marketing product infringed on a broad patent regarding how email works, including how email bounces back when sent to an address that is no longer active.













 Enlarge






                            Brian LaCorte                        










 


Since RPost was threatening to sue GoDaddy (NYSE: GDDY), the domain name registrar and small business tech provider instead decided to “take a stand” in January 2014 and filed its own lawsuit against RPost in January 2014.




Arizona Federal Court Judge James Teilborg agreed with GoDaddy, granting a motion for summary judgment June 7 that said RPost’s patents were invalid and in turn, the issue was moot.
“GoDaddy believes that it is important to vigorously defend itself, and the industries in which it serves, against meritless patent claims, as was the case in this matter,” said Nima Kelly, GoDaddy executive vice president and general counsel, in an email. “We are pleased with the court’s decision showing that the asserted patent claims are invalid and should not be enforced against GoDaddy or anyone else.”
GoDaddy’s legal team said they thought RPost's patents were invalid because they were so broad, said Brian LaCorte, a Ballard Spahr partner and head of the firm’s Phoenix intellectual property team that represented GoDaddy in the case.
“What’s happening in these patent cases is that tech companies are saying these patents are invalid because they cover the most basic abstract concepts,” LaCorte said. “RPost obtained patents that cover the basic functions of how email works. The patents claimed to cover collecting information and tracking email to its point of destination.”
GoDaddy wasn’t seeking money, just a ruling. RPost counter sued for infringement and requested millions of dollars in damages, LaCorte said.




 


The case is the first major decision in the District of Arizona on this issue following a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in Alice Corp. v. CLS Bank International in which the court laid out new guidelines for patent eligibility.

“By invalidating these patents it’s a considerable ruling because it not only allows GoDaddy to operate but it allows other companies in the email marketing space to avoid these RPost patents,” LaCorte said.
In the past, RPost has sued dozens of large tech companies, including Amazon, Adobe and eBay/PayPal, and has many lawsuits still making its way through court involving these patents. RPost is in active litigation against tech companies such as Epsilon, Experian, StrongMail, Docusign and Symantec.
Since GoDaddy is the first to actually get a judgment striking down these patents, it could impact the ongoing cases, LaCorte said.
GoDaddy’s case was set to go to trial in August, but the trial was vacated because of the judge’s decision.
RPost did not respond to an emailed request for comment.
Many tech companies are taking a stand against patent infringement claims by filing suit instead of waiting to be sued, LaCorte said.
“This took a lot of perseverance and diligence,” LaCorte said. “This costs large and small companies a lot of money. At some point, you stand firm and say you’re not going to pay. GoDaddy took a stand and the judge gave good guidance.”

Hayley Ringle covers technology and startups for the Phoenix Business Journal.












